sentences: Juan Tizol Martínez (22 January 1900 – 23 April 1984) was a Puerto Rican jazz trombonist and composer.
In 1920, Tizol joined a band that was traveling to the United States to work in Washington, D.C.
This opened up new possibilities for Ellington's writing, as he now could write for trombones as a section instead of just having them play with the trumpets.
Tizol made many contributions to the Ellington band throughout the 1930s and 1940s.
His best-known compositions, "Caravan" (1936) and "Perdido" (1941), are jazz standards.
His best-known compositions, "Caravan" (1936) and "Perdido" (1941), are jazz standards.

Mercer Ellington stated that Tizol had invented the melody to "Caravan", from his days studying music in Puerto Rico; where they could not afford much sheet music so the teacher turned the music upside down after they had learned to play it right-side up.
Tizol left Ellington's band in 1944 to play in the Harry James Orchestra.
In  1951, he returned to Ellington, along with James's drummer and alto saxophonist, in what became known as 'the James raid'.
However, he returned to James' band in 1953 and remained predominantly on the West Coast for the remainder of his career.
Tizol returned very briefly to Ellington's band in the early 1960s, but eventually retired in Los Angeles.
He died of a heart attack at the age of 84 on April 23, 1984 in Inglewood, California, two years after the death of his wife, Rosebud.
